Prediction of electricity demand

Scenario

You are employed by Enercoop, a cooperative society that has developed thanks to the liberalization of the electricity market in France. It specializes in renewable energies. Most of these renewable energies, however, are intermittent, so it is difficult to predict the capacity of electricity production. In addition, the demand for electricity users varies over time, and depends on parameters such as weather (temperature, brightness, etc.). The challenge is to match supply and demand!

Skills

  • Linear regression
  • Time series (AR, MA, ARMA, ARIMA)
  • Master the ARMA method
  • Graph a time series
  • Master the methods of smoothing and Holt-Winters metho
  • Master the notions of components and decomposition models

# multiplot : Plotting multiple graphs

multiplot <- function(..., plotlist=NULL, file, cols=1, layout=NULL) {
  library(grid)

  # Make a list from the ... arguments and plotlist
  plots <- c(list(...), plotlist)

  numPlots = length(plots)

  # If layout is NULL, then use 'cols' to determine layout
  if (is.null(layout)) {
    # Make the panel
    # ncol: Number of columns of plots
    # nrow: Number of rows needed, calculated from # of cols
    layout <- matrix(seq(1, cols * ceiling(numPlots/cols)),
                    ncol = cols, nrow = ceiling(numPlots/cols))
  }

 if (numPlots==1) {
    print(plots[[1]])

  } else {
    # Set up the page
    grid.newpage()
    pushViewport(viewport(layout = grid.layout(nrow(layout), ncol(layout))))

    # Make each plot, in the correct location
    for (i in 1:numPlots) {
      # Get the i,j matrix positions of the regions that contain this subplot
      matchidx <- as.data.frame(which(layout == i, arr.ind = TRUE))

      print(plots[[i]], vp = viewport(layout.pos.row = matchidx$row,
                                      layout.pos.col = matchidx$col))
    }
  }
}

pdf: 2

Consumption shows:

  • a stable trend over time
  • a seasonality, that is to say, regular variations around the average level, of period 12 (corresponding to an annual period since the series is monthly):
    • the maximum consumption corresponds to the months of December-January-February: logical because it is the winter period where the heating is activated
    • the minimum consumption corresponds to the months of July-August: logical because it is the summer period

    An explanation of the peak in June may be due to the use of a fan / air conditioner during periods of excessive heat. And the drop in July / August can correspond to departures on holidays, companies that close during the summer (so less computer to power, less air conditioners / fans also ...) The DJU (Unified Day Degree) is a value representative of the difference between the temperature of a given day and a pre-established temperature threshold (18 C in the case of DJU or Unified Day Degree). Summed over a period, they make it possible to calculate the heating needs of a building. The higher the number of UDIs, the colder the climate over the period considered. It is therefore coherent that the DJU curve follows the same pattern as that of consumption.

    Assessment of independence¶

    In [22]:
    library(car)
durbinWatsonTest(regr)

    Loading required package: carData

     lag Autocorrelation D-W Statistic p-value
   1      0.06463625      1.828503   0.462
 Alternative hypothesis: rho != 0
    The independence or not of the residues can be represented with the lag plot which represents the value of the residue n + 1 as a function of the value of the residue n. To have a dependence between the residues, a well-defined form must be observed, which is not the case. Moreover, the Durbin Watson statistic is close to 2 p-value> 5%, which is characteristic of an independence of residues: the hypothesis of independence of the residues is thus verified.

    Hypothesis of normality of residues¶

    This hypothesis can be evaluated graphically using a QQplot. If the residues are well distributed along the line on the plot, then the assumption of normality is accepted. Conversely, if they deviate, then the hypothesis of normality is rejected
    In [23]:

    Here, the points are pretty well aligned on the line. The Shapiro-Wilk test can also be used to assess the normality of residues. The normality assumption is rejected if the p-value is less than 0.05.
    In [24]:
    shapiro.test(regr$residuals)

    	Shapiro-Wilk normality test

data:  regr$residuals
W = 0.98414, p-value = 0.7014
    We have a p-value> 5% which leads us to accept the hypothesis H0: the residues are normally distributed.

    Residue homogeneity hypothesis¶

    This hypothesis can be verified in a visual way. It is necessary to realize a "residuals vs fitted plot". The "fitted" correspond to the responses predicted by the model, for the observed values of the predicitive variable. More precisely, for this plot, the square root of the standardized residues is used.
    In [25]:
    # Save figure

dev.off()

# Plotting figure
plot(regr, 3)
    pdf: 2
    Here, the red curve is generally flat. This shows that the residuals tend to be homogeneously distributed throughout the gradient of predicted prestige values. And so the hypothesis of homogeneity of residues is accepted. It is also possible to evaluate this hypothesis using the Breush-Pagan test. The homogeneity assumption is rejected if the p-value is less than 0.05.

    Part 3 - Prediction of consumption (corrected for the temperature effect) over one year by the Holt Winters method (exponential smoothing) and the SARIMA method on the time series

    1. Holt Winters method (exponential smoothing)

    Modeling¶

    The Holt-Winters method, sometimes still used in practice, consists in supposing that Xt is approximate near T by aT + (t-T) bT + ST, where S is the period of the seasonal cycle of the time series.
    In [35]:
    hw=ets(consumption_corr,model="AAA")
    The model used 'AAA' allows to decompose the time series into an error (1st A) + a trend (2nd A) + a seasonality (3rd A). A: for "Additive"

    2. SARIMA method

    Our time series Consumption has a trend and seasonality so it depends on time. So it can not be modeled by an ARMA stationary process. We will therefore stationarize the time series by differentiation.

    Stationnarisation¶

    In [43]:
    # Save figure
png("figure/Figure 17 - ACF : Xt.png", width = 16, height = 9, units = 'in', res = 300)

    pdf: 2
    By observing the simple autocorrelogram of the time series consumption:
  • Simple autocorrelations (h) are neither close to 1 nor close to each other. Thus we do not differentiate in trend.
  • The ACF output of the series shows a slow decrease towards 0 for the multiples of 12. Similar behaviors of simple autorrelations (h) are observed periodically. Indeed, (12) and (24) are quite close, there is a strong correlation / relationship between separate implementations of 12 months. We then perform a differentiation in "seasonality" with s = 12 : differentiation (I-B ^ 12).

    Model identification, estimation and validation¶

    At the end of the stationarization, we obtain a stationary process. There is a theoretical result, called Wold decomposition, which tells us that any stationary process can be modeled by an ARMA process. We can devote ourselves to the potential choices of the polynomial coefficients (p, q, P and Q) by relying respectively on the partial autocorrelogram and the simple autocorrelogram estimated:
    Determination of AR (p) If our differentiated time series (in trend and / or seasonality) is a process AR (p), then a realization X_t only depends on X_ (t-1), X_ (t-2), ... X_ (tp) realizations preceding.

    So X_t has no relation with the realizations X_ (t-p-1) ... X_1. Thus, on the partial autocorrelogram, from the rank p + 1, the r (h) are zero. The r (h) being the autocorrelations between time t and t-h conditionally at intermediate times.
    ** Determination of MA (q) ** If our differentiated time series (in trend and / or seasonality) is a MA (q) process, then an X_t realization can be written as a linear combination of decorrelated disturbances: a white noise and its past.

    So X_t has no connection with the variations of the realizations X_ (t-q-1) ... X_1. Thus, on the simple autocorrelogram, from the rank q + 1, the (h) are zero.

    Determination of ARs (P) and MAs (Q)¶

    The seasonal part of the AR or MA models can be observed by looking at the seasonal lags (12,24 ...) of the ACP and the PACF.
  • For example: an ARIMA model (0,0,0) (0,0,1) [12] will have:
    • a peak at lag 12 in the ACF but no other significant peaks
    • a decrease in seasonal lags in the PACF (ie lags 12, 24, 36 ...)
  • For example: an ARIMA model (0,0,0) (1,0,0) [12] will have:
    • a decrease in seasonal lags in the ACF (ie lags 12, 24, 36 ...)
    • a peak at lag 12 in the PACF but no other significant peaks

    The blue dashed lines are the boundaries of significance (95%). We have :
  • p = 0 because: from lag 1, the partial autocorrelations are not significant
  • P = 1 because:
    • a decrease in seasonal lags in the ACF (ie lags 12, 24, 36 ...)
    • a peak at lag 12 in the PACF but no other significant peaks
  • q = 0 because: from lag 1, simple autocorrelations are not significant
  • Q = 1 because:
    • a peak at lag 12 in the ACF but no other significant peaks
    • a decrease in seasonal lags in the PACF (ie lags 12, 24, 36 ...)

    Model auto : auto.arima¶

    The auto.arima () function of the forecast package automatically generates the optimal coefficients (p, d, q) (P, D, Q). The function involves models and looks for the combination that minimizes the AIC (Akaike Information Criteria): it is a measure of the information lost by the model. The weaker it is, the better the model.
    In [60]:
    model_auto <- auto.arima(consumption_corr, stepwise=TRUE, approximation=TRUE, allowdrift=FALSE)

    The normality of the residues must be verified. Graphically, the residues seem to follow a normal distribution. A null hypothesis Shapiro-Wilk test is performed H0 (residues are normally distributed). We have a p-value> 5% which leads us to accept the hypothesis H0: the residues are normally distributed.
    In [78]:

    Then, in the context of the ARMA models, it is desired that the residue be a white noise (low), that is to say without linear time dependence. Its covariances must be zero. On the ACF, we can notice that the majority of its simple autocorrelations (standardized covariances) are not significant. So graphically, the residue is a white noise. We do a null hypothesis Ljung-Box test H0 (the residues are a white noise). For the majority of lags, we have p-values> 5%, which leads us to partially accept the hypothesis H0.
